        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Imaging: We plan to perform a single pointing map, pointed between B1-bS and B1-bN to encompass both sources, with an angular resolution of ~2.5 arcsec. With this configuration we will derive the density profile up to angular scales of few tens of arcseconds (the maximum angular scale is ~25 arcsec). We will detect possible signtaures of infall motions by observing the profile of the HCO+(1-0) line. To evaluate the optical depth we plan to observe the optically thin isotopologue H13CO+(1-0). Finally, the SiO(2-1) is included to detect outflows. In fact a low velocity outflow in CO(2-1) has been reported recently by Huang &amp; Hirano (2013) [9]. 

Correlator setup: Two side-bands of 2 GHz each are dedicated to the continuum emission. Two side-bands of 58.594 MHz of bandwidth and a spectral resolution of 30.518 kHz will be used for the line emission, one centered on the HCO+(1-0) at 89.188 GHz with 
a velocity resolution of 0.1 km/s, and the other one will be used in 1/2 fractional mode to observe the SiO (2-1) at 
and the other one at 86.847 GHz and the H13CO+(1-0) at 86.754 GHz with a velocity resolution of ~0.2 km/s.

Sensitivity: The integration time is driven by the sensitivity required to observe the H13CO+(1-0) line with a SNR&gt;5, estimated from observations of a sample of young low-mass protostars (Saito et al. 2001) [13], implying a sensitivity of ~6 mJy. 
Therefore, the total observing time in band 3, including calibration and overheads, is 1.37 hours.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
