    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to observe two very young sources, B1-bS and B1-bN, in the Perseus molecular cloud with ALMA. Several recent studies have suggested these two sources are both excellent candidates for the mysterious First Hydrostatic Core (FHSC), a rare stage of star formation which has thus far been predicted but has yet to be detected. To verify the nature of B1-bN and B1-bS, we need high resolution and sensitive continuum and molecular line observations, which only ALMA can uniquely provide. With ALMA, we will observe the two objects in the continuum at 350 GHZ with a spatial resolution of 0.22 arcsec (corresponding to an effective resolution of 0.4 arcsec because of the antennae shadowing, or ~100 AU at the distance of the sources) in order to derive the density and temperature profiles and to resolve the disk, and in molecular lines in band 3 (SiO (2-1), HCO+ (1-0) and H13CO+ (1-0)) in order to reveal infall and outflow motions. These observations will clarify the evolutionary status of the sources. If their FHSC status is confirmed, this will be the very first detection of such early objects.</prp:abstract>
